#compdef pushpin-publish
# ============================================================================
# _pushpin-publish — zsh completion for Pushpin's GRIP / ZeroMQ publish CLI
# ============================================================================
#
# UPSTREAM
#   Repository : https://github.com/fastly/pushpin
#   Author     : Fastly Inc. (formerly Fanout, Inc.)
#   License    : Apache-2.0
#   Stars      : 3848
#   Language   : Rust  (the OG Pushpin was C++; rewritten in Rust)
#   Crate      : pushpin v1.42.0-dev
#   Binary     : pushpin-publish  (Cargo.toml [[bin]] name; `pushpin` parent)
#   Last push  : 2026-05-29
#
# WHAT IT IS
#   Pushpin is "a proxy server for adding push to your API, used at the
#   core of Fastly's Fanout service".  It is a reverse-proxy daemon that
#   sits in front of an HTTP backend, watches the backend's responses for
#   GRIP (Generic Realtime Intermediary Protocol) headers, and converts
#   them into long-poll / HTTP-streaming / Server-Sent-Events / WebSocket
#   push channels — all without the backend itself needing to keep
#   long-lived connections open.  The `pushpin-publish` CLI is the
#   publishing client of the Pushpin family:  it talks to a running
#   Pushpin instance over GRIP-HTTP or a ZeroMQ PUSH socket, submits a
#   payload tagged with a channel name, and the proxy fans it out to all
#   subscribers of that channel.  Common use cases: chat broadcast,
#   live-comment streams, server-side metric pushes, real-time dashboards.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/bin/pushpin-publish.rs
#                       clap-builder Command chain)
#   pushpin-publish [OPTIONS] <CHANNEL> [CONTENT]
#
#   Positional arguments:
#     <CHANNEL>            Channel name to publish to (REQUIRED)
#     [CONTENT]            HTTP body / WebSocket message content
#
#   Identification:
#     --id <ID>            Payload ID
#     --prev-id <ID>       Previous payload ID (for sequencing)
#     --sender <SENDER>    Sender meta value
#
#   HTTP response shaping:
#     --code <CODE>        HTTP response code to use         [default: 200]
#     -H, --header "K: V"  Add HTTP response header (repeatable)
#     -M, --meta "K=V"     Add meta variable (repeatable)
#     --hint               Send a hint instead of content
#     --close              Close streaming and WebSocket connections
#     --patch              Treat CONTENT as a JSON patch
#     --no-seq             Bypass the sequencing buffer
#     --no-eol             Don't append a newline to HTTP payloads
#
#   Transport selection:
#     --spec <SPEC>        GRIP URL or ZeroMQ PUSH spec
#                                          [default: http://localhost:5561]
#                          Examples:
#                            http://example.com:5561         (GRIP HTTP)
#                            tcp://example.com:5560          (ZMQ PUSH)
#                            ipc:///var/run/pushpin/pub      (ZMQ IPC)
#
#   Authentication:
#     -u, --user <USER:PASS>   HTTP Basic auth
#     -B, --bearer <TOKEN>     Bearer auth
#
#   Standard clap auto-flags:
#     -h, --help               Show help
#     --version                Show version
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   Direct dependency on `zmq = "0.9"` declared in Cargo.toml — the
#   canonical Rust ZeroMQ binding (erickt/rust-zmq, the de-facto idiomatic
#   Rust wrapper around the C libzmq).  Pushpin's `publish::run()` uses
#   `zmq::Context::new()` and a `zmq::SocketType::PUSH` socket to send
#   GRIP-encoded messages to the Pushpin handler's ZeroMQ PULL endpoint
#   (the default spec `tcp://localhost:5561` for the ZMQ path).
#   Verified via:
#     gh api repos/fastly/pushpin/contents/Cargo.toml
#       → zmq = "0.9"
#   This entry is the Rust=120 leader bump that OPENS Axis 65
#   (ZeroMQ Messaging Library), pairing with future Go=go-zeromq/zmq4 or
#   pebbe/zmq4 and TS-Node=zeromq.js poles to close the axis at 1/1/1.
#
#   No completion for `pushpin-publish` ships with Apple zsh
#   (/usr/share/zsh/*/functions) or Homebrew zsh-completions
#   (/opt/homebrew/share/zsh/site-functions) — confirmed absent.  The
#   sibling `more_src/_pushpin` exists in this corpus for the parent
#   daemon;  `pushpin-publish` is a separate [[bin]] in the same crate.
# ============================================================================

_pushpin-publish() {
    _arguments -s \
        '--id=[payload ID]:id:' \
        '--prev-id=[previous payload ID for sequencing]:prev id:' \
        '--sender=[sender meta value]:sender:' \
        '--code=[HTTP response code (default 200)]:status code:' \
        '*'{-H+,--header=}'[add HTTP response header (repeatable, "K: V")]:header:' \
        '*'{-M+,--meta=}'[add meta variable (repeatable, "K=V")]:meta:' \
        '--hint[send a hint instead of content]' \
        '--close[close streaming and WebSocket connections]' \
        '--patch[treat content as JSON patch]' \
        '--no-seq[bypass sequencing buffer]' \
        '--no-eol[do not append newline to HTTP payloads]' \
        '--spec=[GRIP URL or ZeroMQ PUSH spec (default http://localhost:5561)]:spec:' \
        '(-u --user)'{-u+,--user=}'[HTTP basic auth (user:pass)]:user\:pass:' \
        '(-B --bearer)'{-B+,--bearer=}'[bearer auth token]:token:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '(- *)--version[show version]' \
        ':channel:' \
        ':content:'
}

_pushpin-publish "$@"
